        "id": 3143,
        "name": "Dave Cottlehuber",
        "username": "dch",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/dch/{size}/473_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-01-26T15:09:52.656Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I\u2019m new to FDB but didn\u2019t find this raised anywhere already - apologies if not.</p>\n<p>I\u2019d like to be able to ensure that there is no way for another user application on the same box to be able to use the TCPIP connection to get direct access to the underlying FDB, and bypass my application\u2019s own security permissions.</p>\n<p>For the reasonably common scenario of the FDB server + client application being co-located, it would be great to be able to use a UDS (UNIX Domain Socket) for connectivity, rather than TCP (+ potentially TLS). This would be faster, and significantly easier to secure. I\u2019m aware that right now I don\u2019t have a working application, and therefore an actual performance/security constraint.</p>\n<p>With UDS I could simply set appropriate file system permissions, and be sure that only root users could bypass that.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 2,
        "updated_at": "2019-01-26T15:09:52.656Z",
        "reply_count": 1,
        "reply_to_post_number": null,
        "quote_count": 0,
