      {
        "id": 3157,
        "name": "Alex Miller",
        "username": "alexmiller",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/alexmiller/{size}/326_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-01-28T23:39:27.728Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"dch\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"1071\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://sea1.discourse-cdn.com/foundationdb/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/dch/48/473_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> dch:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I\u2019d like to be able to ensure that there is no way for another user application on the same box to be able to use the TCPIP connection to get direct access to the underlying FDB, and bypass my application\u2019s own security permissions.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>FDB still needs to be able to talk to another FDB instance, so I\u2019m not clear how one could do <strong>only</strong> a unix domain socket, as you seem to be requesting.  For a client to be able to access the FDB cluster, they\u2019d need a cluster file.  Controlling access to the cluster file would be one way of banning access to the cluster.  Another would be to use the TLS support to ensure that your application is the only one that has an appropriate client certificate to be able to  authenticate to FDB.</p>\n<p>That said, I\u2019d still be in favor of allowing unix domain sockets in addition to a tcp socket to make it easier and faster for FDB clients to access their co-located FDB servers.</p>",
